{{no footnotes|date=December 2011}} The '''Cernavodă culture''', ca. [[4th millennium BC|4000]]—[[32nd century BC|3200]] BC, was a late [[chalcolithic|Copper Age]] [[archaeological culture]]. It was along the lower Eastern [[Southern Bug|Bug River]] and [[Danube]] and along the coast of the [[Black Sea]] and somewhat inland, generally in present-day [[Romania]] and [[Bulgaria]]. It is named after the Romanian town of [[Cernavodă]].
It is a successor to and occupies much the same area as the earlier [[neolithic]] [[Karanovo culture]], for which a [[destruction layer|destruction horizon]] seems to be evident. It is part of the "''Balkan-Danubian complex''" that stretches up the entire length of the river and into northern Germany via the [[Elbe]] and the [[Baden culture]]; its northeastern portion is thought to be ancestral to the [[Usatovo culture]].
It is characterized by [[hill fort|defensive hilltop settlements]]. The pottery shares traits with that found further east {{which|date=November 2017}} on the south-west [[Eurasian steppe]];{{cn|date=November 2017}} burials similarly bear a resemblance to those further east.
== See also == * [[Bronze Age in Romania]] * [[Coțofeni culture]] * [[Basarabi culture]] * [[Otomani culture]] * [[Pecica culture]] * [[Wietenberg culture]] * [[Hamangia culture]] * [[Prehistory of Transylvania]] * [[Prehistoric Romania]]
