{{Infobox Airport | name = 25th Fighter-Bomber Air Base (Cheshnegirovo) | nativename = | ensign = [[File:Roundel of Bulgaria.svg|90px]] | image = File:4e6nigirovo-0-0.jpg | IATA = | ICAO = LBPS | type = Former Military Air Base | owner = | operator = [[Bulgarian Air Force]] | location = [[Cheshnegirovo]], [[Bulgaria]] | elevation-f = 604 | elevation-m = 184 | coordinates = {{coord|42|6|50|N|24|59|29|E|display=inline,title}} | pushpin_map = Bulgaria | pushpin_label = Cheshnegirovo Air Base | pushpin_map_caption = Location within Bulgaria | website = | metric-rwy = | r1-number = | r1-length-m = 2544 x 52 m | r1-length-f = 8345 x 170 ft | r1-surface = [[Concrete]] | footnotes = }}
'''Cheshnegirovo Air Base'''/[[Sadovo]] used to house the 25th Fighter-Bomber Air Regiment (flying MiG-23BN/UBs) of the 10th Combined Air Corps. According to the major restructuring plans it became the first regiment to convert to an air base structure. Briefly it housed the entire Bulgarian [[MiG-23]] fleet after which it disbanded.
==History== Cheshnegirovo Air Base (ICAO code: Z07T) * Inactive * Alternate name Sadovo. Also spelled 'Tcheshnigirovo'. Located in central Bulgaria, north east of Plovdiv. Date when built - 1951. Home of 25 Fighter-Bomber Air Regiment of 10th Composite Air Corps, with the MiG-17. In 1976 it received the MiG-23BN. The base closed in 2000 and is now used for the storage of aircraft. There are reports that the 68 Special Forces Brigade will move here from Plovdiv. {{External media|float=left|image1=[http://tiiim.snimka.bg/reports/aviobaza-cheshnegirovo.708983.28842258 Cheshnegirovo Air Base after close]}} Runway data: Location: N42 06 50.91 E024 59 34.59, Elev: 604 ft (184 m), Rwy 10/28, Size: 8345 x 170 ft (2544 x 52 m), concrete.
