The '''Embassy of Slovakia''' in [[London]] is the [[diplomatic mission]] of [[Slovakia]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/263519/LDL_December_2013.pdf |title=The London Diplomatic List |date=8 December 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211155353/https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/263519/LDL_December_2013.pdf |archivedate=11 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> It is located at the junction of [[Kensington Palace Gardens]] and [[Bayswater Road]] in a building it shares with the [[Embassy of the Czech Republic, London|Embassy of the Czech Republic]].

The Embassy of [[Czechoslovakia]] was originally located on [[Grosvenor Place]], before moving to the location of the current Czech and Slovak embassies in 1970.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.mzv.cz/london/en/about_us/about_the_embassy_building/index.html | title= Architecture of the Embassy | date=8 December 2013}}</ref> The construction of a new [[brutalist]]-style building at this site had begun in 1965 and was undertaken by Jan Bočan, Jan Šrámek and Karel Štěpánský from the [[atelier]] Beta Prague Project Institute; it received an award from the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] for the best building in the United Kingdom created by foreign architects.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.mzv.cz/london/en/about_us/about_the_embassy_building/index.html | title= Architecture of the Embassy | date=8 December 2013}}</ref> The building was then divided between the Czech and Slovak Republics following the [[dissolution of Czechoslovakia]] in 1993.

