{{Infobox diocese |jurisdiction = Diocese |name = Dali |local = 天主教大理教区 |latin = Dioecesis Talianus | image = Dali Catholic Church exterior.JPG | image_size = 230px | image_alt = | caption = Cathedral of the Sacred Heart |country = {{flag|China}} |metropolitan = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Kunming|Kunming]] |province = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Kunming|Kunming]] |rite = [[Latin Rite]] |cathedral = Cathedral of the Sacred Heart in [[Dali City|Dali]] |cocathedral = |area_km2 = |population = 3,212,339 |population_as_of = 1968 |catholics = 5,097 |catholics_percent= 0.2 |pope = {{Incumbent pope}} |bishop = [[Sede Vacante]] |metro_archbishop = [[Sede Vacante]] |coadjutor = |auxiliary_bishops= }}
The '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Dali/Tali''' ({{lang-la|Talian(us)}}, {{zh|大理}}) is a [[diocese]] located in the city of [[Dali City, Yunnan|Dali]] in the [[Ecclesiastical province]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Kunming|Kunming]] in China.
In 2000, the Vatican appointed [[Lawrence Zhang Wen-Chang]] as [[Apostolic Administrator]] of Dali. He served until his death in 2012.<ref name=ucanews>{{cite news|first=|last=|title=‘Underground’ administrator dies|url=http://www.ucanews.com/2012/02/07/await-lucias-imprimatur-check-%E2%80%98underground%E2%80%99-administrator-of-yunnan-dies/|work=[[Union of Catholic Asian News]]|publisher=|date=2012-02-07|accessdate=2012-03-02|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130105013644/http://www.ucanews.com/2012/02/07/await-lucias-imprimatur-check-%E2%80%98underground%E2%80%99-administrator-of-yunnan-dies/|archivedate=2013-01-05|df=}}</ref>
==History== * November 22, 1929: Established as [[Mission “sui iuris”]] of Dali 大理 from the [[Apostolic Vicariate of Yunnanfu]] 雲南府 * December 13, 1931: Promoted as [[Apostolic Prefecture]] of Dali 大理 * December 9, 1948: Promoted as Diocese of Dali 大理
==Leadership== * [[Bishop]]s of Dali 大理 (Roman rite) ** Bishop [[Lucien Bernard Lacoste]] (December 9, 1948 – 1983) * Prefects Apostolic of Dali 大理 (Roman Rite) ** Fr. [[Giovanni Battista Magenties]] (December 13, 1935 – 1947)
